    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_526616787" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/526616787" />
    <a title="TheSmellOfPaper" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12953104-thesmellofpaper"><img alt="TheSmellOfPaper" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1358654594p2/12953104.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/526616787?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="TheSmellOfPaper" class="user" itemprop="url" name="TheSmellOfPaper" href="/user/show/12953104-thesmellofpaper">TheSmellOfPaper</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer526616787" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16162705693053195273">This is the first time I&apos;ve given a 2 and I feel I need to defend it. Clearly, I&apos;m in a minority here versus some heavyweight critics. <br/><br/>While Powers is capable of some gorgeously crafted writing, the reason I opted for &quot;It&apos;s ok&quot; instead of &quot;I liked it&quot; is that to be honest, I didn&apos;t like it. Not because of the subject matter but because I didn&apos;t feel it worked as a novel.<br/><br/>This was written as a novel, not a memoir, so I judged it in terms of the story it told, not the truth it might have been conve</span>
  <span id="freeText16162705693053195273" style="display:none">This is the first time I've given a 2 and I feel I need to defend it. Clearly, I'm in a minority here versus some heavyweight critics. <br /><br />While Powers is capable of some gorgeously crafted writing, the reason I opted for "It's ok" instead of "I liked it" is that to be honest, I didn't like it. Not because of the subject matter but because I didn't feel it worked as a novel.<br /><br />This was written as a novel, not a memoir, so I judged it in terms of the story it told, not the truth it might have been conveying.<br /><br />I read this back to back with Pynchon's The Crying of Lot 49 (which I'd give a 4.5), and there you have a brief novel with the wingspan to take on and invent a whole new world order. In contrast, for me it felt like The Yellow Birds took a central incident that had the makings of a short story, and rolled it out thin till it became a novel. <br /><br />I also felt Powers kept us at arms length throughout the book. Maybe that's a comment on how it feels to witness a war, but I didn't get the feeling that was the point he was making. Instead I got the feeling that this was someone who didn't have enough control over his material. That's in contrast to books about war that I admire like The Things They Carried, and Catch 22.<br /><br />So, on this one, I'll agree to disagree with the critics.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16162705693053195273" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


